{"title":"MotivGraph-SoIQ: Integrating Motivational Knowledge Graphs and Socratic Dialogue for Enhanced LLM Ideation","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"LLM-generated research ideas often lack rigorous motivational grounding in the literature due to probabilistic internal knowledge and limited context, leading to superficial or infeasible proposals.","method":"Introduce MotivGraph, a motivational knowledge graph that encodes research motivations as (problem, challenge, solution) triples with explicit edge types (parent-of, problem–challenge, challenge–solution). Build it automatically via SciMotivMiner, which extracts standardized, author-agnostic triples from papers and merges duplicates, then add a hierarchy using a Parent Node Addition algorithm that embeds nodes, finds nearest neighbors, and leverages an LLM to form general parent nodes. During ideation, agents use graph tools (fuzzy node search and relation retrieval) to ground ideas on concrete nodes from the graph, supplying structured, cross-linked motivational context for each proposal."},{"problem":"LLMs exhibit confirmation bias and weak self-correction, so initial ideas are rarely challenged or substantially improved, leaving core flaws unaddressed.","method":"Develop the Q-Driven Socratic Ideator: a dual-agent loop where a mentor only probes along three axes—innovation, feasibility, and rationality—without giving solutions, while a researcher defends and revises ideas by querying MotivGraph (fuzzy search, relation retrieval), consulting Semantic Scholar, and injecting cross-domain novelty via a random-nodes tool. The process runs for multiple rounds and ends with an ACCEPT/REJECT gate to enforce quality control. Ablations show the mentor loop is essential—removing it substantially reduces quality (e.g., Novelty −0.86, Experiment −0.88, Motivation −0.62)."}]}
